post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_35885836_35885988_0": {"length": 22, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6665}}, "n3337": {"so_35885836_35885988_0": {"length": 22, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6420}}, "n4659": {"so_35885836_35885988_0": {"length": 22, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 8140}}}, "35885836": {"ViewCount": "81", "Body": "<p>Here's a small example that demonstrates my question:</p>\n<pre><code>class Foo {\nprivate:\n  int x;\n  void y() {\n    class Bar {\n    public:\n      Bar(Foo* foo) {\n        foo-&gt;x = 3;\n      }\n    };\n    Bar bar(this);\n  }\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>Class <code>Foo</code>, and a class defined inside its member function <code>y</code> tries to access its private member <code>x</code>. Is this allowed?</p>\n<p>Visual Studio 2013 can compile this, but IntelliSense seems to think that the private members cannot be accessed and does not list them when typing <code>foo-&gt;</code> inside the embedded class methods.</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "35885988", "Title": "Private scope in locally-defined class", "CreationDate": "2016-03-09T07:49:41.430", "Id": "35885836", "CommentCount": "2", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2016-03-09T07:58:45.137", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "1537403", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "35885988": {"Id": "35885988", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The code is valid.</p>\n<p>N4140 [class.access]/2:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_35885836_35885988_0\">A member of a class can also access all the names to which the class has access. A local class of a member\n  function may access the same names that the member function itself may access.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2016-03-09T07:58:45.137", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2016-03-09T07:58:45.137", "ParentId": "35885836", "Score": "5", "OwnerUserId": "3959454"}});